  "prompt": "Household income $280K and able to pay $130K down payment, can I buy a house in San Francisco?",
  "response": "Buying a house in San Francisco with a household income of $280K and a $130K down payment is possible, but it depends on several factors, including the price of the house, your other financial obligations, and current mortgage rates. Here\u2019s a breakdown to help you assess the situation:\n\n### 1. **Affordability Based on Income**\n   - Lenders typically use a **debt-to-income ratio (DTI)** to determine how much you can borrow. A common guideline is that your total monthly housing expenses (mortgage, property taxes, insurance, etc.) should not exceed 28-30% of your gross monthly income.\n   - $280K annual income = **$23.3K monthly income**.\n   - 30% of $23.3K = **$7K/month** for housing expenses.\n\n### 2. **Down Payment**\n   - A $130K down payment is **6.5% of $2M** or **13% of $1M**. \n   - In San Francisco, median home prices are often above $1.5M, so you\u2019ll likely need to consider **jumbo loans** (loans above $1,089,300 in 2023 for most areas in CA).\n   - Jumbo loans often require stricter qualifications (e.g., higher credit scores, lower DTI, and larger down payments).\n\n### 3. **Home Price You Can Afford**\n   - With a $130K down payment and a $7K monthly housing budget, you can estimate the price range:\n     - Assuming a **7% mortgage rate**, **property taxes of 1.25%**, and **homeowners insurance of $2K/year**, you might afford a home priced around **$1.1M to $1.3M**.\n     - This is a rough estimate; exact numbers depend on your specific financial situation and loan terms.\n\n### 4. **San Francisco Market**\n   - The median home price in San Francisco is often **$1.5M or higher**, so you may need to look at smaller homes, condos, or less expensive neighborhoods.\n   - Consider expanding your search to nearby areas (e.g., Daly City, South San Francisco) for more affordable options.\n\n### 5. **Other Costs**\n   - **Closing costs**: Typically 2-5% of the purchase price.\n   - **Homeowners Association (HOA) fees**: Common for condos and townhouses.\n   - **Property taxes**: High in California, often 1.25% or more of the purchase price annually.\n\n### 6. **Next Steps**\n   - **Get Pre-Approved**: Speak with a lender to understand how much you can borrow and at what interest rate.\n   - **Explore Neighborhoods**: Focus on areas within your price range.\n   - **Adjust Expectations**: You may need to consider smaller homes or condos rather than single-family homes.\n\n### Conclusion\nWith a $280K income and $130K down payment, you can likely afford a home in the **$1.1M to $1.3M range**, depending on your other financial obligations and current mortgage rates. While this may not cover the median-priced home in San Francisco, there are still options available, especially if you\u2019re open to condos or less expensive neighborhoods. Consulting a real estate agent and mortgage lender will help you refine your search and understand your options.",
